k9JAzMJtn23w9fSVawCddCfKMZtBtC2mMXfRoqKp.description:
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA): the U.S. law that tells companies, “Keep your bribes in your pockets and your books squeaky-clean.”

Imagine a stern—but surprisingly entertaining—hall monitor for global business:

The “No-Mochi-in-Class” Rule (Anti-Bribery):
It’s illegal for American companies—or anyone listed on a U.S. exchange—to hand out cash, cars, vacations, or world-tour concert tickets to foreign officials just to score contracts. “Grease payments” suddenly became “career-ending sludge.”

The Ledger-Lysol Clause (Accounting Controls):
Companies must keep records so tidy an auditor could eat off them. Fake invoices, double-books, and mystery “consulting fees” get flagged faster than you can say “Enron déjà vu.”

“We’ll Take It from Here” Enforcement:
The DOJ plays bad cop; the SEC plays nerdy cop. Both can slap eye-watering fines, throw executives in orange jumpsuits, or ban them from boardrooms for life. (Seriously—total vibe killer.)

Global Reach-Around:
Even if the shady handshake happens on a yacht in the Maldives, the long arm of U.S. jurisdiction has sunscreen and extradition treaties. “What happens offshore” no longer stays offshore.

Corporate Survival Kit:

Train everyone from interns to CEOs to say “No thanks, I’ll pay for my own caviar.”

Perform due-diligence background checks on third-party agents (yes, that “cousin” in customs counts).

Install whistleblower hotlines so anonymous heroes can save the day—and maybe snag a bounty.

Fun Fact:
The FCPA turned 21 in 1998 and celebrated by teaming up with 44 countries via the OECD Anti-Bribery Convention—basically turning the solo act into a world tour.
